Astra, Energi Mega, Bank Central Asia: Indonesia Equity Preview

-- B y   F e m i   A d i
-- 
2011-03-24T02:08:07Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-24/astra-energi-mega-bank-central-asia-indonesia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are
in parentheses, and share prices are as of the previous close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  advanced 38.51 points, or 1.1
percent, 3,556.23.  Energy companies: Oil fell from the highest since September
2008 in  New York  as U.S. crude inventories rose more than
analysts forecast, overshadowing threats to supplies from the
conflict in  Libya  and Middle East unrest. Oil dropped 0.3
percent to $105.42 a barrel in after-hours trading in New York
as of 8:22 a.m. Jakarta time.  PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ),  Indonesia ’s
biggest listed oil company, was unchanged at 2,800 rupiah and PT
Energi Mega Persada (ENRG IJ), the second largest, rose 0.8
percent to 125 rupiah.  PT Bank Central Asia (BBCA IJ): Net income at the nations’s
largest bank by market value gained 25 percent in 2010 from a
year earlier to 8.52 trillion rupiah on higher non-operational
revenue,  Bisnis Indonesia  reported, citing data obtained by the
newspaper. Bank Central Asia gained 0.7 percent to 6,800 rupiah.  PT Mitra Adiperkasa (MAPI IJ): The Indonesian retailer has
allocated 350 billion rupiah for  capital spending  this year to
add new stores, Bisnis Indonesia reported, citing Corporate
Secretary Fetty Kwartati. The company, which runs Starbucks Corp.
and Burger King Holdings Inc. outlets in Indonesia, gained 2.9
percent to 2,675 rupiah.  PT Astra International (ASII IJ): Indonesia’s February
domestic vehicle sales declined to 69,489 units from 73,866
units a month earlier, the company said, citing data from the
nation’s automotive industries association. Astra, Indonesia’s
biggest automotive retailer, rose 1.5 percent to 55,850 rupiah.  To contact the reporter on this story:
